[
  {
    "text": "A direct comparison can be achieved by applying a threshold to the continuous LSOG probability map to create a discrete presence/absence classification, making it structurally equivalent to the Hagan et al. LiDAR map.",
    "topic": "map-type alignment"
  },
  {
    "text": "An apples-to-apples comparison entails harmonizing the design-based LSOG estimates and the model-based LiDAR classification by summarizing both within common spatial support units (e.g., 100 m grid cells or HUC12 watersheds) and computing bias-corrected agreement statistics.",
    "topic": "inference-framework reconciliation"
  },
  {
    "text": "The LSOG design-based estimation provides pixel-wise probabilities, and when compared to the discrete LiDAR map, the standard approach is to compute area-proportional accuracy metrics using the continuous probabilities without binarization (e.g., cross-entropy or Brier score).",
    "topic": "comparison validity"
  },
  {
    "text": "The phrase 'compared directly' refers to a pixel-to-pixel cross-tabulation after the LSOG probability map has been classified at the optimal FIA-anchored threshold, whereas 'apples-to-apples' emphasizes that the threshold was derived to match the FIA-based prevalence, not an arbitrary cutpoint.",
    "topic": "threshold justification"
  }
]
